article.description: Kayla Pedersen and Jayne Appel each had double-doubles to lead Stanford (No. 4 ESPN/USA Today, No. 3 AP) past South Carolina, 78-47.
article.headline: Pedersen, Appel double team South Carolina to lead Stanford to victory
article.linkText: Pedersen, Appel lead No. 4 Stanford's attack
article.story:
COLUMBIA, S.C. -- Stanford coach Tara VanDerveer has no doubt how the Cardinal (No. 4 ESPN/USA Today, No. 3 AP) got back on track Friday night.

"The focus of our team is on either side of me," said VanDerveer said, flanked by 6-foot-4 stars Kayla Pedersen and Jayne Appel.

If they keep playing like this, it could be a tall order for anyone to slow them down.

Pedersen and Appel each had double-doubles Friday night in a 78-47 win over the Gamecocks, as Stanford (8-2) recovered from a loss to Duke that opened its three-game East Coast swing earlier this week.

The Cardinal close the weeklong stretch at Tennessee (No. 13 ESPN/USA Today, No. 11 AP) on Sunday in a rematch of last spring's NCAA championship game won handily by the Lady Vols.

However, after a sluggish performance in falling to the Blue Devils, 56-52, VanDerveer and her club made beating South Carolina their priority.

"This was a must game for us in terms of coming out and playing very, very well," VanDerveer said. "Our team was very disappointed at how we played against Duke and how we finished that game. I think we wanted to show ourselves we were better than that."

They might have also shown off one of the country's most dominant front lines.

Pedersen had 15 points and a tied her career high with 16 rebounds. Appel finished with 15 points and 14 rebounds. They led a dominating display under the boards for Stanford, which outrebounded the Gamecocks 53-21.

"We don't really get outrebounded like we did tonight," said first-year South Carolina coach Dawn Staley.

For the Gamecocks (5-4), it was their 20th straight loss to a ranked opponent. The team is 1-38 since the end of the 2002-03 season in such games, the lone victory coming three years ago against Minnesota.

That's part of why Staley left her successful gig at Temple to revive the Gamecocks.

While she got an upclose view at how height can help -- Stanford has six players 6-3 or taller, South Carolina has two -- "I'll take four midgets that can play," Staley joked.

Appel had two baskets and Pedersen a pair of foul shots to put Stanford ahead 18-8. However, the Gamecocks kept scratching back against their much taller opponents.

The Cardinal wore down South Carolina and pulled away after halftime. They opened with a 16-5 run that stretched their lead to 20 points and were never pushed the rest of the way.

Stanford held South Carolina to five field goals in the second half. With the Cardinal packed in tight around the basket, the Gamecocks failed to take advantage, going 1-of-15 on mostly open 3-pointers.

Appel told her teammates not to peek ahead to Tennessee, no matter how tempting it was to think about revenge against the Lady Vols.

"This was going to establish the type of tone we wanted to play," Appel said.

And now that the Cardinal can fully prepare for Tennessee?

"I'm very excited," Appel said. "I'll leave it at that."

The Stanford-South Carolina game was a reunion of several key members of the 1996 U.S. women's Olympic team. VanDerveer led that group, which featured most of South Carolina's coaching staff in Staley and her assistants Nikki McCray and Carla McGhee.

VanDerveer hugged each of them before and after, wishing them good fortune in the difficult Southeastern Conference.

"If she tells she ever beat me in chess, she's lying," VanDerveer said of Staley, then a precocious, fiery point guard. "She's a very competitive person and I think she's a very fabulous basketball coach."

Also in attendance was basketball great Anne Donovan, who won Olympic gold in 1984 and 1988 and led the U.S. women to Olympic gold in Beijing. Staley, who owns three golds as a player, was an assistant for the American team.
